# Force LF for files that EXECUTE on Linux (the EC2 box). The dev machine is Windows
# with core.autocrlf=true, which makes `git archive` inject CRLF into shell scripts and
# systemd units → `$'\r': command not found` / `set: pipefail<CR>: invalid option` at
# runtime on the box. eol=lf pins LF in the working tree AND in `git archive` output,
# independent of the local autocrlf setting. (Found 2026-06-30 during the CloudWatch
# publisher deploy; protects the ADR-0032 cutover scripts too.)
*.sh      text eol=lf
*.service text eol=lf
*.timer   text eol=lf

# Repo-wide binary formats. Never EOL-converted anywhere.
*.gz      binary
*.zip     binary
*.npz     binary
*.parquet binary
*.duckdb  binary
*.sqlite  binary
*.xlsx    binary
*.docx    binary
*.pptx    binary
*.pdf     binary
*.png     binary
*.jpg     binary

# ======================================================================================
# MR-002 EVIDENCE TREE — text is a WHITELIST, not a default.
#
# The previous policy was a single line:
#
#     docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/**   text eol=lf
#
# written to protect the countersigned markdown, whose SHA-256 binding is over LF bytes. But `**`
# matches EVERYTHING in the tree, including the gzipped archives. Git marked them text, and its
# clean filter strips the CR from any CRLF byte pair occurring inside the COMPRESSED STREAM — where
# 0d 0a is data, not a line ending. Seven of the nine archives carry such pairs (anchors.csv.gz has
# 8; raw_response_manifest.jsonl.gz has 48). A single `git add` would have deleted those bytes and
# destroyed the archive. They showed as permanently "modified" while being byte-identical to HEAD,
# which is the symptom of precisely this.
#
# Blacklisting the binary extensions fixes today's tree and re-arms the trap for tomorrow's: the
# next `.zip`, `.npz` or `.pkl` dropped in here would be matched by `**` and by no binary rule.
#
# So the default for this tree is NO CONVERSION, and the text formats are named explicitly. A new
# binary format is then safe by default, and a new TEXT format simply is not normalized until
# someone adds it here — which is the failure that costs nothing.
# ======================================================================================
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/**              -text

docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/*.md            text eol=lf
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/*.json          text eol=lf
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/*.csv           text eol=lf
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/*.txt           text eol=lf
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/*.sha256        text eol=lf
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/**/*.md         text eol=lf
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/**/*.json       text eol=lf
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/**/*.csv        text eol=lf
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/**/*.txt        text eol=lf
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/**/*.sha256     text eol=lf

# The countersigned pre-registration: the owner's countersign binds an exact SHA-256 of the file
# BYTES. With core.autocrlf=true a fresh clone would materialize these as CRLF (MR-002 v1.1 rev 3:
# 35,053 B LF -> 35,688 B CRLF), producing a different hash and silently voiding the binding.
docs/implementation/TradingWorkbench_MR002_PreRegistration_*.md text eol=lf
